  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT216-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">paruva varaviṉkaṇ āṟṟāḷ eṉak kavaṉṟa tōḻikkuk kiḻatti uraittatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by HER to the confidante who was anxious she
          wouldn’t have the strength at the coming of the season. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT216">
        <lg type="edition">

          <l>avarē</l>
          <l>kēṭil viḻupporu ṭarumār pācilai</l>
          <l>vāṭā vaḷḷiyaṅ kāṭiṟan tōrē</l>
          <l>yāṉē</l>
          <l>tōṭā relvaḷai nekiḻa vēṅkip</l>
          <l>pāṭamai cēkkaiyiṟ paṭarkūrn ticiṉē</l>
          <l>yaṉṉa ḷaḷiya ḷeṉṉātu māmaḻai</l>
          <l>yiṉṉum peyya muḻaṅki</l>
          <l>miṉṉun tōḻiyeṉ ṉiṉṉuyir kuṟittē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">

          <l>He,</l>
          <l>he is one who, in order to bring imperishable excellent wealth,</l>
          <l>traversed the wilderness of evergreen<note place="foot">Is <term xml:lang="ta">pacu
            ilai vāṭā</term> an attribute of general impact, that is, Vaḷḷi leaves which are always
            green, or is it just momentary, green Vaḷḷi leaves not yet faded?</note> creepers.</l>
          <l>I,</l>
          <l>so that my many precious bright bangles become loose, I lament</l>
          <l>[and] suffer affliction in abundance on a sleepless <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">amai cēkkai</term> : is this a "bed on which sleep becomes still",
            that is, stops? Or the other way round: "bed on which one, actually, sleeps deep?</note>
            bed.</l>
          <l>Without saying: “as she [is] she [is] pitiable!” the black cloud,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">thundering, so that it will rain now too,</l>
          <l>flashes lightning, friend, intent on my sweet life.<note place="foot">A second
            possibility of construction is circular syntax, i.e. the absolutive <term xml:lang="ta">
            kurittu </term> also with <term xml:lang="ta">avar/iṟantōr</term> as a subject: "He, he
            is one who ... traversed the wilderness ... having marked my sweet life, where the black
            cloud makes thunder and lightning ...".</note></l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
